Democratic presidential nominee Joe Biden is closing in on securing enough electoral votes to take the White House after a much closer election result than many expected. Democracy Now! co-host Juan González says that as results come in, there's a false narrative by political commentators and mainstream media outlets that Black and Latinx voters have underperformed at the polls. "The real underperformers this election were white voters," says González. "Why are all the commentators not dissecting what the heck is going on in white America and with white women in America?"

Watch the full segment on democracynow.org (link in bio).

node.text: Fuck Christopher Columbus. We are raising money so that there are no cold elders on Navajo land this winter. Chizh For Cheii began as an idea that turned into a movement of love, hope and inspiration. Last year’s season has never stopped for CFC, as our wood hauling ended covid began to hit Navajo land and communities hard. CFC members quickly transitioned to providing mutual aid in form of giving out hundreds of food boxes, water and cleaning supplies for weeks on end.” Also, I lost the source for this doc, does anyone know it or can tag any of the folks in this video?

“I do think I was born under a very bright star” RBG passed as we were entering shabbat and Rosh Hashanah, the gateway to a new year. This is a time where we as a community contemplate what it means to be human, live a good life, and who we are growing ourselves into. She left us so much space, and gave us permission, if we need it, to be relentless in our pursuit of justice. May her memory be a part of our revolution. 

“According to Jewish tradition, a person who dies on Rosh Hashanah, which began tonight, is a tzaddik, a person of great righteousness," Ruth Franklin

“A Jewish teaching says those who die just before the Jewish new year are the ones God has held back until the last moment bc they were needed most & were the most righteous." -Nina Totenberg

node.text:
I wrote and recorded The Week Ahead last Monday, before I had heard about Hurricane Ida - without knowing how my words would land given the situation. 

In light of Hurricane Ida’s impact, we wanted to share some local resources and mutual aid networks supporting relief workers on the ground in New Orleans. 

@imaginewaterworks is a Native, Creole, queer, trans-led organization that supports climate justice, water management, and disaster readiness and response. This fund goes directly to relief efforts led by locals.

@anothergulf.ispossible is a Women of Color-led, grassroots collaborative focused on cultural organizing, arts-based healing, direct action, advocacy, transformative justice, and education. They are distributing donations directly to: Indigenous, Black, and Brown frontline folks, individual families impacted by the storm, + groups who currently don’t have online donations capacity.

Please swipe for information on how to donate and take a look at our stories for direct links to their donation pages.

Please add any others below that you know and trust. 
.
🧿 Sending protection and energy to all who are displaced and struggling right now. Please donate if you can and share these orgs and more with your networks! If you are being impacted and need assistance please drop your Venmo and cash app etc below! 
.
#MutualAid #HurricaneIda

Happy baby Moon, bbs! As the New Moon breaks the seal of a new lunar cycle, we get to Priestess our hopes and dreams into being. 
.
